  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1663633786" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1663633786" />
    <a title="Roman Clodia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56111743-roman-clodia"><img alt="Roman Clodia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1464021031p2/56111743.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1663633786?book_show_action=true">Jun 09, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Roman Clodia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Roman Clodia" href="/user/show/56111743-roman-clodia">Roman Clodia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141182858" href="/book/show/829372.Wide_Sargasso_Sea">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/56111743-roman-clodia?shelf=contested-heritage-work">contested-heritage-work</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1663633786" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12204902265508196683"><br/><br/>I&apos;m blown away by this book all over again and am in awe of the magnificent way that Rhys deftly layers her art: Antoinette is both character - melancholy, traumatised by her family history, exploited, and menaced in so many ways - but she&apos;s also a figure who might stand in for a British West Indian colonial history which many people want to mute or hide away, but which still finds ways, however brutal and disturbing, to assert itself and wander the corridors of the archetypal Victorian &apos;great h</span>
  <span id="freeText12204902265508196683" style="display:none"><br /><br />I'm blown away by this book all over again and am in awe of the magnificent way that Rhys deftly layers her art: Antoinette is both character - melancholy, traumatised by her family history, exploited, and menaced in so many ways - but she's also a figure who might stand in for a British West Indian colonial history which many people want to mute or hide away, but which still finds ways, however brutal and disturbing, to assert itself and wander the corridors of the archetypal Victorian 'great house' of Thornfield Grange. She is described as a ghost in the third part which intersects with <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/10210.Jane_Eyre" title="Jane Eyre by Charlotte Brontë" rel="nofollow noopener">Jane Eyre</a> but is also afraid of seeing the ghost that is embodied in her own experience - this specific colonial legacy, via Antoinette, becomes a form of English haunting. <br /><br />I also noted this time round how cleverly proleptic Rhys' text is with fires and burning a repeated image, from the firing of Coulibri, the previously slave-worked sugar plantation house, to the moths which dash themselves against the candle flames recalling ideas of passion and destruction. <br /><br />Rhys is particularly adept at form: the three houses - Coulibri, the 'sweet honeymoon house' near the village of Massacre, and Thornfield echo the structural houses that trace Jane Eyre's original journey. And the use of narrative voices, shifting between Antoinette herself and Edward Rochester, is exemplary, showing us his descent into something close to incoherence as his self-fashioning narrative draws to a close, and questioning her status as 'mad' given the contrasting coherence, however confused, of her own text. <br /><br />Immensely sophisticated, that Rhys manages to say so much in 120 pages is a stunning achievement. With so much to think about, this Penguin edition with introduction, appendix, general notes and textual notes is helpful and illuminating.<br />-----------------------------------------------<br />(Original review)<br /><br />In this passionate, poetic and intense book, Jean Rhys writes back to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/10210.Jane_Eyre" title="Jane Eyre by Charlotte Brontë" rel="nofollow noopener">Jane Eyre</a>, inverting the patterns of that book and turning `the madwoman in the attic' from silenced object of other people's discourse to a woman with a voice and subjectivity of her own.<br /><br />In three parts, this fragmentary novel gives us Antoinette's difficult childhood as a Creole (regarded as neither `white' nor `black' in post-Emancipation Jamaica), a middle narrative from Mr Rochester telling of their marriage, and a short final part from Antoinette again (now re-named by him as Bertha) from her imprisonment in the attic.<br /><br />Like Rhys' other books, this gives a voice to a traditionally muted female character but she overlays the gender concerns with an interest in a colonial legacy. The idea of the `Other' is shown to be simultaneously constructed in terms of race, gender, class and `normality' (though whether Antoinette is `mad' or not is certainly questioned by the text).<br /><br />That said, Rhys doesn't make this a predictable book and is most contrary, I think, in the central section where Rochester falls deeply under the spell of Antoinette - and it is his fear of her effect on him, perhaps, which he sees as most dangerous.<br /><br />So this is a very modern re-writing of a well-loved book, de-centreing the story of Jane Eyre and forcing us to see it anew. It is also a text which lends itself very well to postcolonial and gendered readings.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12204902265508196683" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


