    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_399318048" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/399318048" />
    <a title="Jenn(ifer)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/780933-jenn-ifer"><img alt="Jenn(ifer)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1623352942p2/780933.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/399318048?book_show_action=true">Aug 24, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jenn(ifer)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jenn(ifer)" href="/user/show/780933-jenn-ifer">Jenn(ifer)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/889028.Wide_Sargasso_Sea">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">those who have already read Jane Eyre</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Jenn(ifer) by: </span>
      I would never have found Jean if not for Mariel
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/780933-jenn-ifer?shelf=my-reviews-that-dont-suck">my-reviews-that-dont-suck</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/780933-jenn-ifer?shelf=read-in-2012">read-in-2012</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/780933-jenn-ifer?shelf=summer-of-women-2012">summer-of-women-2012</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/780933-jenn-ifer?shelf=xx">xx</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer399318048" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6161997500976096621"><br/>As many of you who read my reviews are aware, I had devoted this summer to exclusively reading female writers, as my reading list was woefully lacking in books written by the fairer sex. It has been an exceptional experience for me as it has opened my eyes to such great writers as Flannery O’Connor, Virginia Woolf, Alice Munro and the incomparable Jean Rhys.<br/><br/>Jean Rhys! I feel I owe a debt to the original publishers of <i>Wide Sargasso Sea</i> because if not for its publication her exceptional early work</span>
  <span id="freeText6161997500976096621" style="display:none"><br />As many of you who read my reviews are aware, I had devoted this summer to exclusively reading female writers, as my reading list was woefully lacking in books written by the fairer sex. It has been an exceptional experience for me as it has opened my eyes to such great writers as Flannery O’Connor, Virginia Woolf, Alice Munro and the incomparable Jean Rhys.<br /><br />Jean Rhys! I feel I owe a debt to the original publishers of <i>Wide Sargasso Sea</i> because if not for its publication her exceptional early work may have remained for ever out of print and I may never have been introduced to Jean. The Jean of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/144073.Good_Morning__Midnight__Penguin_Modern_Classics_" title="Good Morning, Midnight (Penguin Modern Classics) by Jean Rhys" rel="nofollow noopener">Good Morning, Midnight</a>. The Jean of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/144069.After_Leaving_Mr__Mackenzie" title="After Leaving Mr. Mackenzie by Jean Rhys" rel="nofollow noopener">After Leaving Mr. Mackenzie</a>. She is my soul mate (if I believed in that sort of thing). We are kindred spirits.<br /><br />You see, back in the 1930’s, before the second world war when young Jean’s novels were published, they didn’t catch on with the general public. Maybe people just didn’t get her (don’t worry, Jean, I get you). They met with some critical acclaim, but widespread readership was not to be had. So with that, Jean vanished from the literary scene and spent the next twenty years living in relative obscurity. It wasn’t until the end of the 1950’s that she was located and it was discovered that she had been working on the manuscript for <i>Wide Sargasso Sea</i>. With <i>Wide Sargasso Sea</i>, Jean finally received much deserved recognition for her body of work, although with her failing health she often remarked that this recognition came ‘too late.’<br /><br />So let’s talk about <i>Wide Sargasso Sea</i>. If this had been my introduction to Jean Rhys, I don’t think I would have cared to read the rest of her work. Because, for me, this is not representative of Jean’s writing. I like the <i>idea</i> behind it. To take the frightening lunatic from <i>Jane Eyre</i> and give her a voice, tell her background, tell her story; it’s a remarkable idea. But the execution… of that I’m not convinced. It was all too heavy handed; it lacked the subtlety of her earlier work. It’s as if Jean put all of the pieces together too neatly for me and didn’t leave any room for me to have my own feelings. <br /><br />I’ll try to explain what I mean by giving you examples of two songs about loss. One is Harry Nilsson’s ‘Without You’ <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_bQGRRolrg0">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_bQGRR...</a> and the other is Glen Hansard’s ‘Leave’ <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TB4RlKFrw3s">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TB4RlK...</a>. Nilsson not only writes with beautiful simplicity, but he doesn’t put it all out there for you; he holds back just enough to keep your interest. He leaves something out, allowing the listener to fill in the blanks. There’s a subtlety to it; like secrets he hasn’t told. Wanting to know the secrets, we listen to that song again and again. That might not make sense yet, but maybe it will after you listen to the Hansard song. Yes, he writes beautifully and yes he makes you feel his loss, but damn, he sucks the air out of the room so there’s nothing left for the rest of us breathe! Stop punching me in the stomach, Glen, I get the point already. <br /><br />Damn. It pains me to write this review. I don’t want Jean tied to Glen Hansard in my memory. I want Nilsson! Thankfully, I saved <i>Quartet</i> for last. For those of you who haven’t read Jean Rhys, or those who don’t feel particularly attached to her early work, you may want to read some of the other reviews that have praised <i>WSS</i>. As for me, my heart is a little bruised today because I’m left with this taste in my mouth after finishing the final pages. It is the taste of mediocrity. But as I said in the beginning, without <i>WSS</i>, Jean would have disappeared into obscurity and who knows if her early body of work would have ever again seen the light of day. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6161997500976096621" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


